nText" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m=
4c3o81"><div class=3D"textBlock"><p>The spherical coordinates calculator is=
 a tool that <strong>converts between rectangular and spherical coordinate =
systems</strong>. It describes the position of a point in a three-dimension=
al space, similarly to our <a href=3D"https://www.omnicalculator.com/math/c=
ylindrical-coordinates" class=3D"js-link">cylindrical coordinates calculato=
r</a>. For a two-dimensional space, instead of using this Cartesian to sphe=
rical converter, you should head to the <a href=3D"https://www.omnicalculat=
or.com/math/cartesian-to-polar" class=3D"js-link">polar coordinates calcula=
tor</a>.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-testid=3D"article-sec=
tion-ads" class=3D"css-r3vyni e1m68soa1"><div class=3D"evuvjg40 MuiBox-root=
 css-19hq6"><div data-testid=3D"desktop_content_1" id=3D"desktop_content_1"=
 ot-name=3D"Desktop_Content_1" class=3D"sc-jrAFXE sc-kEjbQP sc-iqHYmW DZVSn=
 iymrLc jhNEow" ot-addisplayed=3D"true" ot-device=3D"[&quot;Desktop&quot;,&=
quot;Tablet&quot;]"></div></div></section><section data-testid=3D"articleSe=
ction-0" data-cwv-id=3D"calculator-article-section" id=3D"rectangular-and-s=
pherical-coordinates" class=3D"css-qtz96j e1taq3sq0"><h2 data-testid=3D"art=
icleSectionHeader-0" class=3D"css-1xbj7gb">Rectangular and spherical coordi=
nates</h2><div data-testid=3D"articleSectionText" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq=
3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><figure class=3D"imageBl=
ock__image-align--right" style=3D"width: 50%;"><img src=3D"https://upload.w=
ikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/4f/3D_Spherical.svg/558px-3D_Spheric=
al.svg.png" alt=3D"Spherical coordinates" class=3D"imageBlock" loading=3D"l=
azy" width=3D"100%"><figcaption>Source: <span class=3D"js-external-link-but=
ton link-like" data-href=3D"https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:3D_Sphe=
rical.svg" role=3D"button" tabindex=3D"0">Wikimedia</span></figcaption></fi=
gure><div class=3D"textBlock"><p>Coordinates are sets of values that descri=
be the position of any given point in space. For a three-dimensional space,=
 you need precisely <strong>three coordinates</strong> to define a point un=
iquely.</p>
<p>The Cartesian system, also known as the rectangular coordinate system, i=
s constructed by drawing three lines in space. They all cross a common poin=
t, called the <strong>origin</strong>, and are perpendicular to one another=
. These lines are called the <strong>axes</strong> of the system. Each pair=
 of axes defines a plane: these are called the XY, XZ, and YZ planes. The c=
oordinates of any arbitrary point are defined as the distance between that =
point and the planes.</p>
<p>We define the spherical coordinate system by a fixed <strong>origin</str=
ong> and a <strong>zenith direction</strong>. The zenith is an imaginary po=
int located directly above the origin. The direction from the origin to the=
 zenith is called the zenith direction.</p>
<p>Each arbitrary point in space has three spherical coordinates. The first=
 one, called <strong>radial distance</strong> or <strong>radius</strong> (<=
strong>r</strong>), is simply the <a href=3D"https://www.omnicalculator.com=
/math/3d-distance" class=3D"js-link">three-dimensional distance</a> between=
 the origin and this point. The second one - the <strong>polar angle</stron=
g> (<strong>=CE=B8</strong>) - is the angle from the zenith direction to th=
e line that connects the point with the origin. The third one is called the=
 <strong>azimuth angle</strong> (<strong>=CF=86</strong>).</p>
<p>When you create a reference plane that passes through the origin and is =
orthogonal to the zenith, then <strong>=CF=86</strong> is the angle between=
 the point's orthogonal projection to the plane and a fixed reference direc=
tion on that plane.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-testid=3D"=
articleSection-1" data-cwv-id=3D"calculator-article-section" id=3D"converti=
ng-cartesian-to-spherical" class=3D"css-qtz96j e1taq3sq0"><h2 data-testid=
=3D"articleSectionHeader-1" class=3D"css-1xbj7gb">Converting Cartesian to s=
pherical</h2><div data-testid=3D"articleSectionText" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1=
taq3sq1"><div class=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div class=3D"textBlo=
ck"><p>When converting from the rectangular to the spherical system, our sp=
herical coordinate calculator assumes that the <strong>origins of both syst=
ems overlap</strong>. It also assumes that the z-axis is equivalent to the =
zenith direction. The spherical reference plane coincides with the XY plane=
.</p>
<p>You should use the following formulas for the conversion:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>r =3D =E2=88=9A(x=C2=B2 + y=C2=B2 + z=C2=B2)</strong>;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>=CE=B8 =3D arccos(z/r)</strong>;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>=CF=86 =3D arctan(y/x)</strong>,</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>where:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>(x, y, z)</strong> - Cartesian coordinates; and</li>
<li><strong>(r, =CE=B8, =CF=86)</strong> - Spherical coordinates.</li>
</ul></div></div></div></section><section data-testid=3D"articleSection-2" =
data-cwv-id=3D"calculator-article-section" id=3D"converting-spherical-to-ca=
rtesian" class=3D"css-qtz96j e1taq3sq0"><h2 data-testid=3D"articleSectionHe=
ader-2" class=3D"css-1xbj7gb">Converting spherical to Cartesian</h2><div da=
ta-testid=3D"articleSectionText" class=3D"css-h9evcv e1taq3sq1"><div class=
=3D"ed4x0bn0 css-48o5u4 e1m4c3o81"><div class=3D"textBlock"><p>The spherica=
l coordinates calculator is also able to recalculate the spherical coordina=
tes into rectangular ones. It uses the following equations:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>x =3D r =C3=97 sin =CE=B8 =C3=97 cos =CF=86</strong>;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>y =3D r =C3=97 sin =CE=B8 =C3=97 sin =CF=86</strong>;</p>
</li>
<li>
<p><strong>z =3D r =C3=97 cos =CE=B8</strong>.</p>
</li>
</ul>
<p>Don't forget to check our other coordinate geometry calculators like the=
 <a href=3D"https://www.omnicalculator.com/math/average-rate-of-change" cla=
ss=3D"js-link">average rate of change calculator</a>.</p></div></div></div>=
</section></div><div class=3D"MuiPaper-root MuiPaper-elevation MuiPaper-rou=
nded MuiPaper-elevation1 MuiAccordion-root MuiAccordion-rounded e1dypxhm0 c=
